# useMemo

`useMemo` caches the result of a function between renders. It only recomputes when dependencies change.

## Syntax

```jsx
const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => computeExpensiveValue(a, b), [a, b]);
```

The function runs during rendering, so it should be pure and not too slow (or it will block rendering).

## When to Use

* Expensive calculations (e.g., filtering large lists, complex math).
* Stabilizing an object/array that is passed as a prop to memoized children.

## Example

```jsx
function ExpensiveComponent({ list, filter }) {
  const filteredList = useMemo(() => {
    return list.filter(item => item.includes(filter));
  }, [list, filter]);

  return <List data={filteredList} />;
}
```

Without `useMemo`, `filteredList` would be recalculated on every render, even if `list` and `filter` haven't changed.

